previous: Further developed Yak-42M, with two underwing Aviadvigatel PS-90 turbofans. Design evolved into Irkut MC-21.[19]
A projected but unbuilt stretched airliner. Planned to be powered by three Progress D-436 turbofans, a stretched fuselage and new wings. Design developed into Yak-242.[18]
doc.after: As of June 2014, a total of 54 Yakovlev Yak-42 aircraft remain in airline service.[20]
